ce:section.ce:para:
In order to investigate the reproducibility of the optimum CQDs550/TiO2 and CQDs450/TiO2 (with 4 wt% of CQDs), the photocatalytic performance of nanocomposites samples in degradation reaction of methylene blue have been investigated during 6 successive cyclic operations under visible light irradiation (Fig. 12
                     ). Following each cyclic run, the used photocatalysts were centrifuged at 8000 rpm to be completely separated from the solution, and they were then rinsed with ethanol and water repeatedly. As can be observed in Fig. 12, after six successive cycles, the CQDs550/TiO2 and CQDs450/TiO2 nanocomposites retained 88 % and 83 % of their initial photocatalytic activity, which indicates that the synthesized nanocomposites have good stability and cyclability in the photocatalytic degradation of organic contaminants under visible light. Nevertheless, the decrease in the performance observed in Fig. 12 may be explained by the gradual accumulation of the intermediate species resulting from the MB decomposition reaction during cyclic operations [75]. In addition, as Akhavan et al. reported, some chemical species on the surface of carbon nanoparticles may be decomposed as a result of electron transfer between carbon nanoparticles and TiO2 
                     [76]. This phenomenon is in good accordance with the mechanism proposed in the current study according to which the electron transfer from excited CQDs to TiO2 nanoparticles under visible light (reaction 17) can cause oxidation of surface atoms on carbon quantum dots and gradual dissolution of carbon nanoparticles from nanocomposite structure.
